2. STORYBOARD PANELS — 12 to 24 panels arranged on multi-panel pages. Each panel includes:
  • The drawing (rough is fine — story matters more than rendering)
  • A shot description (camera angle, movement, lens choice)
  • Action notes
  • Dialogue or sound notes
  
3. ANIMATIC (optional, +20% portfolio weight) — The storyboard panels assembled into a timed sequence with rough audio. Premiere, After Effects, or any video editor works. 30–90 seconds of finished animatic.

4. SHOT LIST — A spreadsheet or document listing every shot with: shot number, shot size (EWS / WS / MS / CU / ECU), camera movement, duration, and one-line description. This is the production-ready document.

5. WRITTEN REFLECTION — 200 words. What's the story about? What were the hardest decisions? What changes between the script and the storyboard, and why?`,
      },
      {
        heading: 'Shot vocabulary — from DMA 072',
        body: `Joe's DMA 072 storyboarding module establishes the working shot vocabulary. Memorize these — they're how you talk about shots with directors and editors.

Shot sizes (camera distance from subject):
• Extreme Long Shot (EWS / Establishing) — subject tiny in a vast environment. Establishes location and scale.
• Long Shot (LS) — full figure visible with environmental context.
• Medium Shot (MS) — subject from waist up. Conversation distance.
• Close-Up (CU) — head and shoulders. Emotional weight.
• Extreme Close-Up (ECU) — a single eye, an object detail. Maximum intensity.

Camera angles:
• High angle — looking down at subject. Subject diminished.
• Low angle — looking up. Subject empowered or threatening.
• Eye level — neutral. Default.
• Dutch tilt (canted angle) — frame tilted off-axis. Unease, instability.

Camera movement:
• Pan — camera rotates horizontally on a fixed point.
• Tilt — camera rotates vertically on a fixed point.
• Dolly / Truck — camera physically moves through space.
• Zoom — lens magnification changes; camera stays still.
• Rack focus — focus shifts between subjects without camera moving.

In storyboards, indicate camera movement with arrows on the panel. Static panels have no arrows. Panels with movement have arrows showing direction and a label (DOLLY IN, PAN LEFT, etc.).`,
      },
      {
        heading: 'Why scripts are in Courier',
        body: `Industry-standard scripts are typed in Courier 12pt for a specific production reason: one page of properly formatted Courier script equals approximately one minute of screen time.

This is the convention because:
• Courier is monospaced — every character takes the same width
• Standard margins and indentation create a predictable density
• Producers, directors, and editors can estimate runtime from page count at a glance

If you write your script in Helvetica or Times New Roman, the timing math breaks. The format isn't aesthetic — it's a measurement system.

Per DMA 072: dialogue is indented further than action. Character names go above their dialogue, centered. Scene headings (sluglines) are in all caps and tell you where and when each scene occurs. Page breaks happen at logical narrative beats.

A free tool that handles all of this: Highland 2 (Mac), Trelby (Win/Mac/Linux), or Google Docs with a screenplay template.`,
