        heading: 'Workflow',
        body: `Step 1: Write the script. One to three pages, Courier 12pt, standard screenplay format. Don't draw anything yet — the script is the planning layer. If the story doesn't work in prose, it won't work in panels.

Step 2: Beat out the story. Read your script. Identify the major story beats — usually 8 to 15 of them. Each beat becomes at least one panel.

Step 3: Thumbnail every beat. Small, fast sketches. Don't render — just block in composition, shot size, and direction of action. The thumbnails are the storyboard's storyboard.

Step 4: Build the full panel set. Refine the thumbnails into the deliverable storyboard panels. Add shot descriptions, action notes, dialogue. Rough drawing is fine — clear staging matters more than polished rendering.

Step 5: Test it. Show the storyboard to someone who hasn't read the script. They should be able to tell you what happens, when, and why. If they can't, the storyboard isn't working — diagnose which panels are unclear, fix them.

Step 6 (optional): Animatic. Scan the panels, drop them into a video editor on a timeline matching the script duration, add temporary audio. The animatic is where you discover timing problems that the static storyboard hides.`,
