      {
        heading: 'What this track is for',
        body: `Book covers and children's book illustration are publishing-industry deliverables — they sit at the intersection of illustration and graphic design, and they require holding two skills at once: the image has to work, and the typography has to work with the image.

This track produces either:

• ONE FINISHED BOOK COVER for a real or fictitious book — front cover, spine, back cover, fully laid out as a print-ready cover spread.

OR

• ONE FINISHED CHILDREN'S BOOK SPREAD plus supporting work — a full two-page spread for a fictitious children's book, with a thumbnail dummy of the full book (10-12 spreads in rough form) showing how the book holds together.

Pick this track if you want to build a portfolio piece aimed at publishing, editorial work, or children's media.`,
      },
      {
        heading: 'The brief specifics',
        body: `Your brief should answer:

• Real book or fictitious? You can design a cover for a real existing book (great for portfolio comparisons — your version vs. the published version) or for a fictitious book you invent.

• Adult or children's? The two have radically different design conventions and audiences.

• Genre? Literary fiction, sci-fi, romance, thriller, biography, picture book, middle-grade, young adult. Each genre has typography and image conventions.

• Format? Hardcover, paperback, trade paperback, picture book? Each has specific dimensions.

• Standard sizes:
  • Trade paperback: 5.5 × 8.5"
  • Hardcover novel: 6 × 9"
  • Children's picture book: 10 × 8" or 10 × 10" (often square)
  • Children's chapter book: 5.5 × 7.5"`,
      },
      {
        heading: 'Required deliverables — book cover route',
        body: `1. FULL COVER SPREAD — Front + spine + back, laid out as a single print-ready file. Include bleed (0.125" on all sides). Standard hardcover dimensions: 12.25 × 9.25" with 1" spine = a final flat spread of 13.5 × 9.25" plus bleed.

2. FRONT COVER ALONE — The front cover isolated as a separate file. This is what shows up in marketing.

3. THUMBNAILS — At least 12 thumbnail cover sketches exploring different conceptual directions. Black and white, small, fast.

4. TYPOGRAPHY SYSTEM — A one-page document showing the title typeface, author typeface, any taglines or pull-quotes, and how they relate to the illustrated elements.

5. CONTEXT MOCKUP — One image showing the book on a shelf with other books, or held in a hand, or photographed against a background. Proves the cover works in the wild.

6. WRITTEN BRIEF — 200 words. What is the book about? Who is its audience? What is the cover promising the reader?`,
      },
      {
        heading: "Required deliverables — children's book route",
        body: `1. FINISHED SPREAD — One full two-page spread, finished to publication quality. Standard size: 20 × 10" at 300 DPI for a 10 × 10" book (each page is 10 × 10", spread is 20 × 10").

2. STORYBOARD DUMMY — A thumbnail dummy of the entire book showing all 12-16 spreads in rough form. Black and white sketches, small, fast. Proves you've thought about the book as a whole, not just the one spread.

3. CHARACTER DESIGN — At least one character sheet showing the protagonist (or main character pair) in multiple poses and expressions. Children's books require character consistency across many pages — the design has to be repeatable.

4. TYPOGRAPHY PLAN — How text and image relate. Children's book text often runs in unusual placements — over illustrations, integrated with characters, in shaped text blocks. Show the plan.

5. THE STORY — A one-page written version of the book's text. Could be a real children's book you're adapting, or one you've written. The dummy thumbnails should match this text page by page.

6. WRITTEN BRIEF — 200 words. What age is this for? What does the book teach or tell? Why this story?`,
      },
      {
        heading: 'Two reference traditions worth knowing',
        body: `Paul Rand — Children's books as design objects.

Paul Rand collaborated with his wife Ann Rand on a series of innovative children's books in the 1950s and 60s — including "Listen! Listen!" — that treated typography itself as illustration. Type became character. Letters became creatures. Words on the page were not captions for pictures; they were the pictures.

This lineage answers: how can typography be the illustration rather than label it?

Piet Zwart — Modernist book covers.

The Dutch modernist Piet Zwart designed book covers in the late 1920s and early 1930s — including the "Monografieën over Filmkunst" series (1931) — that demonstrated how Constructivist principles could organize covers. Strong asymmetry, photographic elements integrated with typography, hierarchies built from contrast rather than ornament.

This lineage answers: how can a cover communicate a book's content through structure rather than literal illustration?

Both lineages are taught in DMA 010. Pick the lineage that matches your brief — children's book work leans Rand, literary or design-conscious adult covers lean Zwart.`,
      },
      {
        heading: 'Workflow',
        body: `Step 1: Read or write the book. You cannot design a cover for a book you don't understand. If it's a real book, identify the tone, the central question, the audience. If it's a fictitious book, write a one-page summary first.

Step 2: Find the cover concept. A great cover does one thing well — it makes one promise to the reader. Catalog three to five possible promises ("this book is unsettling," "this book is funny," "this book is romantic," "this book is intellectually rigorous"). Pick the strongest. The cover delivers that one promise.

Step 3: Thumbnail 12 covers. Black and white. Two minutes per thumbnail. The strongest will reveal itself.

Step 4: Typography first, image second. Counter-intuitive but reliable: lay out the title and author type before drawing the image. The type takes up surprising real estate. Designing the image first usually forces awkward type placement later.

Step 5: Build the cover. Use the typography from step 4 as the foundation. The illustration fills the remaining space, supports the typography, and delivers the promise from step 2.

Step 6: Test in context. Print the cover at actual size. Hold it. Photograph it on a shelf. A cover that works on screen often fails in physical context — and most book buying still happens with physical books or at thumbnail size in online stores. Both contexts have to work.`,
      },
    ],
  },
};

