But the modern understanding of sequence emerged from the same 19th-century investigations that led to film. In 1824, Peter Mark Roget presented a paper called "Explanation of an optical deception in the appearance of spokes of a wheel when viewed through vertical apertures" — the first scientific examination of how the eye perceives motion through still images. This led to optical toys like the Phenakistoscope (1832), the Zoetrope (1834), and the Praxinoscope (1877).

In December 1888, Charles-Émile Reynaud unveiled the Théâtre Optique, which projected sequential painted images on a screen. On October 28, 1892, at the Musée Grévin in Paris, he showed Pauvre Pierrot — the first public animation film, 15 minutes of individually painted images.

